Dr. G. R. Fitterer


  H G. J. Moseley, a British physicist, was educated
      at Eton and Oxford. He was one of the earliest
to do intensive research on radioactivity. Among other
things, he established the relationship between the
X-Ray spectrum of an element and its atomic number.
He was far ahead of his time, Nevertheless, he was
drafted in the first World War for ordinary sea duty
and was killed in action on August 10, 1915 at the
early age of 28. Britian and the world lost one of its
most brilliant minds and since that time England has
not drafted her engineers and scientists except for
work in their specialized fields.
  This country, however, continues to draft exper-
ienced scientists and engineers because Congress has
not found a means of making exceptions in a democ-
racy such as ours. By the time the present draft law
runs out next June, it is highly possible that we will
have a modified form of Universal Military Training,,
in which some boys will still be drafted for two years
service
  If we are required to defend ourselves ten years
from now, the boys who have been through U. M. T.
may be some use to us as engineers, but if we are en-
gaged in conflict sooner than that, we must rely on
the current supply of engineers and scientists to carry
on the most highly technical warfare the world will
have ever known.
  At the present time we actually have a two year
U. M. T. although it doesn't go by that name. Anyone
who has had an opportunity to observe the situation,
as have the engineering educators, will agree that
under the present situation all engineers are being
drafted before they reach the age of 26. The draft
boards have been letting them receive their education,
then put in several years of industrial work usually
on the military equipment research or development.
Then, just as they are able to make their most valu-
able contributions, they are drafted and usually for
infantry duty.
  Congress, the President, and the Public should be
aroused at Secretary of Defense Wilson's comment at


Quantico, Virginia in June, in which he estimated
that our technological lead over Russia has recently
been cut from 50 years to two or three.
   Recent figures of the Engineering and Scientific
 Manpower Commission indicated that in 1953, 24,000
 engineers received their degrees in the United States.
 Of these approximately 6,000 were in R. O. T. C. and
 many have since been drafted. On the other ha:nd
 Russia graduated 43,000 engineers in 1953 and it. is
 doubtful that they are drafting them for infantry
 service.
   Recent headlines have read as follows:
     "Billion Earmarked for Robot Arms"
     "Ike Breaks Ground for
     First Atomic Power Plant"
     "American Island to be 5,000 Mile
     Target for Guided Missiles"
   How can the services continue to develop these de-
 vices far in advance of the Russians without a con-
 tinuons flow of young Engineers and Scientists?
   There is at least one answer - create a Science and
Engineering Military Reserve in which these special-
lized personnel can enlist for active and or reserve
duty. This would create a known science and engin-
eering manpower pool upon which the various milit-
ary services and defense industries could draw upon
appeal to a civilian - military board. Engineers have
never avoided military duty, and their service records
are well known, In fact, they are highly desired by the
services. Engineers merely feel that if the next war is
to be a push-button conflict they should be per-
mitted to work without interuption in the develop-
ment of technological equipment for the soldier in
the field. Undoubtedly, the infantry is needed, but
it should be equipped with superior weapons. This
can best be done through the formation of a Science
and Engineering Military Reserve as mentioned above.
Our best minds should be utilized for technological
developments and the democratic processes will also
have been served.


