  B  ack around the year 1700, when Sir Isacc Newton
     came to the conclusion that for every action there
must be an equal and opposite reaction,. he probably
didn't have any idea that he would become famous
for such an outwardly simple thought.
  But this statement of a relation of natural pheno-
mena has been the basis for all static and dynamic
problems concerning exerted forces, and has certainly
pointed him out as one of the world's greatest scien-
tists and philosophers. His law has been one of the
cornerstones in the development of the power plant.
  In these power plants, where both action and re-
action exist, it is the action which is most sought for
use and the reaction claims attention only because of
the need .for providing anchorage against it. However,
in one of the newer applications of Newton's law -
jet propulsion - it is the reaction which is used for
motion, and the action is merely an means of provid-
ing it.
  For example, in a gas turbine electric generating


