plant, the turbine is securely mounted to the floor to
anchor the forward thrust reaction caused by the rear-
ward action of the jet stream. Naturally, this is be-
cause the function of this power plant is to use the
action of the jet stream to drive a turbine and thense
a generator to transform kinetic energy into electrical
energy. If this gas turbine were not anchored, the
reaction causing the forward thrust would move the
plant forward, using its energy in the form of motion,
or iet propulsion.
  In all forms of thermal jet propulsion (not includ-
ing rockets which carry their own oxygen), air is
taken into a duct, compressed by some means to the
necessary pressure ratio for efficient operation, com-
bined with the fuel, and ignited. The burning gases
then have a greatly increased velocity and are acceler-
ated out the rear of the duct (action) with an ensuing
forward thrust (reaction) causing the duct to be pro-
pelled forward.
  Enclosed in an aerodynamic shape with a fuel sup-
ply and ignition system, this duct can provide enough
thrust to carry an airplane or missle over a consider-
able range at speeds well above the speed of sound.
As an example consider the ram jet (or athodyd - an
aerodynamic thermodynamic duct), the simplest of


