the three basic types of jets.
  Considerable wartime research was spent on this
form of jet propulsion which is nothing more than
a streamlined converging-diverging tube with a fuel
injection and electric ignition system. In operation,
air is compressed by the configuration of the duct,
fuel is sprayed into the duct and combines with the
compressed air and is then ignited. The combustion
increases the velocity and temperature of the air caus-
ing a jet stream which then diverges from the rear
of the duct propelling the body forward.
  This form of propulsion has been applied to heli-
copter rotor tips an a means of driving them, to an
experimental pilotless plane called the "Drone" and
a supersonic craft designed by a Frenchman named
La duc to fly at four times the speed of sound
(Mach 4).
  The chief drawback of the ram jet is the fact that,
when the duct is stationary, the exhaust from the
explosion of the fuel will blow out of the duct in
both directions, hense air must be rammed in to force
the exhaust of jet stream out the rear.
