Piezoelectric Crystals


  In 1880 Jacques and Pierre Curie, of radium fame,
    discovered that when weights were placed on cer-
tain crystals, electric charges, measured by an electro-
meter, were produced proportional to the applied
weight. The converse effect of displacement of strain
caused by an applied voltage was predicted theoretic-
ally by Lippman in the following year and was verified
by the Messrs. Curie.
  "Piezo, a Greek word meaning "to Press", was ap-
propriately applied to this method of producing elec-
tricity to give the word piezoelectricity. These func-
tions of applied pressure-produced voltage known as
the generator function, or applied     voltage-strain
known as the motor function, and some non-pressure
properties. which piezoelectric crystals exhibit, make
piezoelectricity versatile and useful. Piezoelectricity
differs from electrostriction, such as occurs in the
dielectric of a Leyden jar, in that the strain is re-
versed upon reversal of the polarity of the applied
potential.


