  Several synthetic materials, along with natural
quartz, posses piezoelectric properties. All of these
materials with the exception ot specially developed
ceramics, which are polarized after molding, are cryst-
als. These crystals, the most important being Rochelle
salt, produce the piezoelectric effect because they have
no center of gravity to seperate, causing a strain when
voltage is applied to the crystal in the proper direction.
To get different types of expansion the crystals are
cut on different angles with respect to the axes of
the crystals. Standards for the determination of the
axes of crystals and angle designations have been set
up by the Institute of Radio Engineers. Different
types of possible cuts are, as shown in Fig. 1, Thick-
ness shear, Face shear, thickness expansion and Trans-
verse expansion. Figure 2 shows some piezoelectric
crystals mounting and driving methods. With one end
of a crystals blocked the other end has twice amplitude
of vibration it would have if both the ends were free.
  The first noted application of piezoelectricity came
in World War I when French scientist Langevin was
commissioned to devise a method for detecting sub-
marines. By sandwiching a mosaic of quartz crystals
between two steel plates, which acted as electrodes,
and applying a high frequency voltage, longitudinal
waves were formed which, upon echoing back to the
plates were detected. With a 40,000 cps. applied to a
20 cm square plate, a wave of 5x10 -5 cm amplitude
is sent out and a returning wave of as small an ampli-
tude as 10-10 cm, which is about 1/300 of the diam-
eter of a molecule, can be detected. This was the first
sonar detector.
  Applications of applied pressure-produced voltages
are the hydrophone and under water transducer, which
have many thin sheets of crystals stacked together to
reduce impedance." In the accelerometer, a stack of
crystals, with a weight placed on top to increase sen-
sitivity, produce a voltage proportional to the acceler-
ation. Shaking tables are made using a high frequency
voltage to cause many stacks of crystals to deform
cyclically and, therefore, to vibrate a table top which
sits on the crystals.
  By cementing two sheets of crystals with their axes
in different directions, a twisting or bending effect,
caused by the sheets expanding in different directions,
is obtained when voltage is applied. This twisting or
bending effect is analogous to the action of the bime-



