Dr. Calvert


  D r. John Fyfer Calvert, whose work in the elec-
      trical engineering field has brought him nation-
al recognition became the head of the electrical en-
gineering department at the University of Pittsburgh
on the first of August.
  Prior to his coming to Pitt, Dr Calvert was a pro-
fessor of electrical engineering at Northwestern Uni-
versity since 1938. He was formerly an associate pro-
fessor at Iowa State College.
  Born in Columbia, Missouri, Dr. Calvert entered
the University of Missouri, but was called to active
duty with the national guard after completing one
year of his studies. After serving nine months on the
Mexican border he was shipped overseas where he
participated in three minor and two major engage-
ments in France for which he was awarded the purple
heart, Returning to school, he received the bachelor
of science degree in 1922 and the degree of electrical
engineering in 1924. During the time he was working
for the latter degree he spent one year in the West-
inghouse student course, and joined that company as
an electrical engineer in 1924, remaining until 1936.
  At Westinghouse he designed turbine generators,
propulsion equipment, motors for testing airplane
propellors and high frequency generators. In 1936 he
aided in the rehabilitation of machinery following the
distastrous St. Patrick's Day flood.
  From 1936 to 1938 Dr. Calvert served as consultant
on rural electrification projects for the Iowa State


