Planning Board and associate professor of electrical
engineering at Iowa State College. He went to North-
western as professor of electrical engineering in 1938
and became chairman of the department in 1939. It
was at this time that plans were made for the new
Technological Institute building there and Dr. Calvert
was responsible for the design and selection of equip-
ment for the electrical engineering department.
  In 1941 Dr. Calvert was loaned to the Navy and
directed the initial construction of a ship demag-
netizing station in Maryland. Later he was in charge
of the design and construction of the Pacific Demag-
netizing Station at Pearl Harbor For this work he
earned a Navy citation.
  Dr. Calvert is a fellow of the American Institute of
Electrical Engineers, a senior member of the Institute
of Radio Engineers and a member of the American
Association for the Advancement of Science, the West-
ern Society of Engineers, American Society for Engin-
eering Education, Eta Kappa Nu, Sigma Xi, and Tau
Beta Pi. He was awarded his master of science degree
at Pitt in 1930 and the Doctor of Philosophy degree
in mathematics and engineering in 1936.
  Dr. Calvert has had approximately fifty papers and
technical discussions published and has been granted
six United States patents.
  The University of Pittsburgh is lucky to have a man
like John Calvert to head the Electrical Engineering
department here.


