a seperate committee for each department of the En-
gineering Schools. Each of these departmental com-
mittees is made up of two alumni members, one non
alumnus, and an ex-officio member, the department
head. Each man who was asked to serve on these
committees is a proven leader in industry today. They
each know just what industry needs in a young en-
gineer, both in the way of theoretical and practical
applications in their chosen fields.'
  These men together with the department heads and
the Dean, will review the long term future trend of
each specific branch of engineering and determine
the needs with respect to faculties, equipment and
space necessary to develop the department towards


