  Another type, the resonant duct or pulse jet ap-
peared during World War II and was used very ef-
fectively by the Germans against England in the form
of the "buzz bomb". Also known as the V-1, this missile
was nothing more than a bomb with a puise jet at-
tach to propel it. It was very inefficient but light,
simple, inexpensive to construct, and served its pur-
pose very well. Although few ever hit their target,
the noise produced by the resonent tube was very "dis-
turbing and sent people scattering for shelter, thus
slowing down production at a time when every minute
counted.
  The pulse jet was a resonant-duct ram jet with flap
valves which opened to allow air in and cl&sed when
the burning fuel raised the pressure within the duct,
thus preventing exhaust from leaving both ends of
the duct.
  Following each explosion, a sound wave and hot
gases exhausted from the duct inducing a partialvac-
uum and opening the flaps. More air entered and
mixed with the fuel which was continuously sprayed
in. This cycle was repeated as much as 40 time'sper
second, and after the duct became hot enough, ignit-
ion would take place by residual flame, eliminating
the need for the electric spark.
  The biggest disadvantages were that the duct had
to be of correct length to harmonize the impulse
waves of the explosion with the natural period of os-
cillation of the valves; and that, like the ram jet, it
was not self starting, but had to be launched at an
initial velocity by means of rockets, a catapult, or a
mother aircraft. It is capable of both subsonic and
supersonic speeds depending on the application and
design.
  The third and most complex type of jet propulsion,
the turbo jet, or aircraft gas turbine, makes use of
the same principle of acceleration of the air by the
combustion of fuel in it, but uses an adiabatic ex-
pansion in the duct to impart high velocity to the
products of combustion. This expansion necessitates


a pressure drop of the air. Since the main purpose of
the compression is for increased efficiency, and since
the turbojet duct is not straight thru and does not
compress the air by its geometric configuration alone
as the ram jet, a compressor was installed to increase
the combustion pressure, and a turbine on the same
shaft to drive the compressor.
  Between the discharge from    the compressor and
the turbine entrance, the air is heated and given high
velocity and increased volume by direct combustion
of the fuel. Energy is then extracted by the turbine
to drive the compressor. A sufficiently high energy
level is reached in combustion so that when the tur-
bine work is extracted there is enough energy left to
impart the final high velocity of the jet for forward
thrust of the engine.
  Other types of jet propulsion are the turbo-prop
and the rocket. The turbo-prop is essentially a turbo-
jet with a propellor geared to the turbine compressor
shaft. In effect it just replaces the reciprocating air-
plane engine with a turbojet engine while keeping
the propellor. It does have the advantage of producing
a small amount of thermal jet thrust besides deliver-
ing the needed shaft horsepower to drive the propellor.
  The rocket is essentially a jet, closed at the front
end eliminating the air intake), and carrying its own
oxygen supply for combustion. Although limited in
