  Piezoelectric crystals perform functions which would
make them important even if they did not possess
transducer properties. These functions are electric
storage, optical, electro optical, condenser, and im-
pedance. The electric storage function offers great
promise in the electric computer field. Certain piezo-
electric crystals, especially barium titanate, can be used
in the memory banks where electric signals can be
received and stored away for future use. In the case
of the optical function many piezoelectric crystals
are transparent and double refracting, and because
they give a distinctive color pattern can be effectively
used in gun sights where the color aids sighting. Due
to the superiority of these crystals in ultra-violet trans-
mission, they are used in ultra-violet spectographs.
The electro optical function makes possible the high
speed photography necessary to get pictures at atomic
bomb blasts, by changing the voltage on a piezoelectric
crystal its degree of transparency is instantaneously
changed. If a very short pulse of voltage is applied,
this electric shutter can be "opened" and "closed" in a
much shorter time than mechanical shutters. By using
these crystals as light vales on television cameras and
movie cameras the camerman can regulate the amount
of light pass ing through the lens by changing the
applied voltage. The condenser function of piezo
electric materials has resulted in the small circular
disc condensers used widely in the television field.
These condensers are very rugged, have a high dielect-
ric constant, and possess a very -large capacitance in a
small size. Perhaps the most important non-pressure
function of piezoelectric crystals is their impedance
function. At certain frequencies, because they possess
a high Q value, piezoelectric crystals act as sharply
tuned curcuits. Quartz in particular, possesses this
property. Quartz crystals with Q's of the order of
500,000 are readily available and Q's as high as 6,000,
000 have been measured in the laboratories. Crystals
having high Q's are used in filter and oscillator cir-
cuits in place of fixed tuned circuits. A. M. Nicolson
at the Bell Telephone Laboratories first controlled an
oscillator by means of crystal in 1917. Today, crystals
are used for direct control of frequency in radio trans-


