mitting stations. A quartz clock having a vibrating
quartz plate replacing a swinging pendulum gives
time more constant than the best astronomical clocks.
Both Greenwich Observatory in England and the
Bureau of Standards in Washington, D. C., use quartz
crystals as primary standards. During the second
World War in one year the military used 30,000,
000 crystals in communications equipment to con-
trol frequency alone. Crystal filters are used in coaxial
cables to seperate the simultaneous conversations that
go over one pair of wires. In a fully equipped section
of coaxial cable for carrier communication, with 400
circuits, 12,000 crystals are used for channel filters
only.
  Piezoelectricity is certainly versatile, having seven
seperate and distinct functions of motor, generator,
electric storage, optical, electro-optical, condenser and
impedance. With all these functions the applications
of piezoelectricity are unlimited. In this article only
a few of the better known and most common appli-
cations have been mentioned. With the small size of
piezoelectric crystals and the small sized transistors,
and miniaturized circuit components being developed,
much work can be done by the young engineer in
miniaturizing present circuits and equipment, besides
making many new discoveries which will aid mankind.
The ue of piezoelectricity is limited only by the
imagination of the engineer.


